{"name":"IPv6, DHCPv6","content":"#Concept\n\n##Rules:\n\n- Can drop a block of zeroes and any leading zeros\n- 16 Hexidecimal chracters\n- 128 bits\n\n##Types\n\nUnicast: One to One\nMulticast: One to Many\nAnycast: One to Closest (give the same IP to multiple devices, then finds the closest IP to the client)\n\nNo more broadcasts - mutlicast is a replacement\n\n##Multiple IP Addresses\n\n###1. Link Local: layer 2 domain\n\n* used for communication only in the LAN infrastructure\n\nFE80::/64\n\n##EUI-64 - use MAC address as host ID and inserts FFFE in the middle\n\neg. 11:22:33:44:55:66\n\nbecomes \n\n1122:33FF:FE44:5566 for host ID\n\nFull IPV6 IP: FE80:0000:0000:0000:1122:33FF:FE44:5566 or FE80::1122:33FF:FE44:5566\n\n###2. Unique/Site-Local Scope Address (Private)\n\n\n##3. Global Addresses\n\nAlways begins with 2000::/3 as handed out by IANA\n\n\n#Configuration\n\n\\#ipv6 unicast-routing\n    (config-if)\\#ipv6 address 2001:55::1/64\n\n    \\#ping ipv6 2001:210:10:1::1\n\n    \\#ipv6 route 2001:56::/64 2001:210:10:1::2\n\n    (config)\\#ipv6 router ospf 1\n\n        (config-rtr)\\#router-id 2.2.2.2 (otherwise picks the higest ipv4 automatically)\n\n    (config-if)\\#ipv6 ospf 1 area 0\n\n\n\n","notebook":"32da721510abcbc5","id":"1cc4ae061072f7e0","date":1381926794}